goals.question: What is the distribution of count?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the frequency distribution of the number of trips made between origin and destination.

goals.question: What is the average distance between origin and destination?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the central tendency and variability of the distance between origin and destination.

goals.question: What are the top 10 most popular origin-destination pairs?
goals.visualization: Bar chart of origin-destination pairs by count
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us identify the most frequently traveled origin-destination pairs.

goals.question: What is the relationship between distance and count?
goals.visualization: Scatter plot of distance vs count
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if there is any correlation between the distance between origin and destination and the number of trips made.

goals.question: What is the distribution of distance?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the frequency distribution of the distance between origin and destination.

code:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.hist(data['count'], bins=20, color='blue', edgecolor='black')
    plt.axvline(data['count'].mean(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label='Mean')
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('What is the distribution of count?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['distance'] = pd.to_numeric(data['distance'], errors='coerce')
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))
    ax.boxplot(data['distance'], vert=False, showmeans=True, meanline=True, 
               labels=['Distance'])
    ax.set_title('What is the average distance between origin and destination?')
    ax.axvline(data['distance'].mean(), color='r', linestyle='--', 
               label=f'Mean: {data["distance"].mean():0.2f}')
    ax.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data = data.sort_values(by='count', ascending=False).head(10)
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))
    ax.bar(data['origin'] + ' to ' + data['destination'], data['count'], color='blue')
    ax.set_xlabel('Origin-Destination Pairs')
    ax.set_ylabel('Count')
    ax.set_title('What are the top 10 most popular origin-destination pairs?')
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    ax.scatter(data['distance'], data['count'])
    ax.set_xlabel('Distance')
    ax.set_ylabel('Count')
    plt.title('What is the relationship between distance and count?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['distance'].plot(kind='hist', bins=20, color='blue', edgecolor='black')
    plt.axvline(data['distance'].mean(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label=f"Mean: {data['distance'].mean():0.2f}")
    plt.axvline(data['distance'].median(), color='green', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label=f"Median: {data['distance'].median():0.2f}")
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('What is the distribution of distance?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
